Justinian calls the media iurisprudentia, or more precisely the inter- pretatio (General Introd. p. 45 supr.) of the lex Voconia by the jurists; ‘feminae ad hereditates legitimas ultra consanguineas successiones nou admittuntur, idque iure civili Voconiana ratione videtur effectum: ceterum lex duodecim tabularum nulla discretione sexus adgnatos admittit’ Paul. sent. rec. 4. o 22. Remoter female agnates than sisters had a praetorias title only; they could obtain bonorum possessio in the third rank, as cognates (proximitatis nomine), unless excluded by nearer relations os the same class. Justinian's enactment restoring to them their original rights is in Cod. 6. 58. 14.
